    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201112/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-12"><time>2020-11-12</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE| ARTS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>To get the grande dame of dystopia as fes­ti­val head­liner is quite a coup, even if only vir­tu­ally.</p>
    <p>The Cana­dian author (above) of The Hand­maid’s Tale (1985) and the Mad­dAd­dam tril­ogy (2003 to 2013) dis­sected struc­tures of power and spoke frankly about the con­tro­ver­sial open let­ter against “cen­so­ri­ous­ness” that she signed in July.</p>
    <p>Bleakly pre­scient though her fic­tion may seem, she said she re­mains “re­al­is­ti­cally hope­ful” for the fu­ture be­yond the pan­demic. “We will get to the other side.”</p>

